                'title'   => 'Brain-Computer Interfaces Expand Beyond Medical Applications',
                'summary' => 'Advances in non-invasive neural recording and Neuralink\'s FDA-approved implant platform are opening BCI technology to consumer wellness, communication, and productivity use cases.',
                'content' => "Brain-computer interfaces have historically been confined to clinical settings — helping patients with ALS communicate or enabling paralyzed individuals to control prosthetics. In 2026, two parallel tracks are expanding BCI into broader applications: Neuralink's surgical implant platform has received FDA approval for a second indication covering treatment-resistant depression, and non-invasive EEG-based wearables have achieved sufficient signal quality for practical consumer use cases.\n\nNeuralink's N2 device, implanted in over 400 patients globally as of early 2026, enables high-bandwidth bidirectional communication between neurons and external devices. Beyond paralysis, researchers are reporting remarkable results in accelerated language learning, cognitive rehabilitation after traumatic brain injury, and real-time mood monitoring for psychiatric conditions. The ethical debates around brain data privacy, device security, and the boundary between treatment and enhancement have intensified correspondingly.\n\nOn the non-invasive side, companies like Neurosity, Emotiv, and OpenBCI have released wearable headsets achieving 256-channel dry EEG with consumer-grade ease of use. Machine learning models trained on large neural datasets can now reliably decode attentional states, emotional valence, and coarse motor intentions. Applications range from attention-adaptive focus tools and meditation feedback to gaming controllers and accessibility devices for people with motor impairments.\n\nThe regulatory landscape is fragmenting by geography. The FDA is developing a specific regulatory pathway for cognitive enhancement BCIs that sits between medical devices and consumer electronics. The EU is more restrictive, requiring clinical evidence for any device making wellness claims about neurological function. China has fast-tracked approvals for several domestic BCI manufacturers targeting industrial focus monitoring applications.",
